NAME: 'Bronze Beauty'
NARRATIVE: Selection from corn grown by the Winnebago Tribe, Wisconsin Dells, Wisconsin. Selected for 3 years by E. A. Hynek for productivity by eliminating only poor yielding individuals. It is a flint corn with a high frequency of bronze or tan kernels.  Red kernels also segregate.  It differs from many U.S. Northern Flints by having narrower kernels on tapered ears with a higher kernel row number.

This acccession can therefore be associated with the Lenape (Delaware Indian) tribe.

COLLECTION SITE: From Koehler, New Madrid, Missouri. New Madrid county.

NAME: White Dent
NARRATIVE: NA

NAME: Hays Golden
NARRATIVE: Medium early variety well adapted to western Kansas.  Very drought resistant.
COLLECTION SITE: From Hays Branch Station in 1923 from Ness County and further selected at the Station.

NAME: Labette County Yellow
NARRATIVE: Full season variety. Yielded well in test crosses. Drought resistant.

NAME: Midland Showears
NARRATIVE: NA
COLLECTION SITE: From George Wilkerson, Sedalia, Missouri. Pettis county.

NAME: Boone County White
NARRATIVE: NA
COLLECTION SITE: From Dixie Hightower, Walker, Missouri. Vernon county.

NAME: Yellow Dent
NARRATIVE: NA
COLLECTION SITE: From Ralph Gundy, Eldorado Springs, Missouri. Cedar county.

NAME: Baxters Golden Bantam
NARRATIVE: Yellow sweet type. Plants of medium height, late, much suckered and free from smut; stalks purple; ears 13.5 by 4.5cm, 12 rowed; seeds yellow, sweet.

NAME: G 8824
NARRATIVE: White capped dent. Whitecap version of 'Lancaster Sure Crop' Plants vigorous, erect, leafy with whorls of leaves at top and suckerless. Severe smut. Ears 10 by 2.25", 14 rowed.

NAME: G 8827
NARRATIVE: Yellow dent. Plants vigorous, erect, uniform and leafy with few suckers. Susceptible to smut. Ears 8.5 by 2.25", 16 rowed.

NAME: G 8834
NARRATIVE: Yellow dent. Plants vigorous, erect, suckerless, moderately uniform and leafy. Susceptible to smut. Ears 10 by 2.25", 16 rowed.

NAME: Cash White
NARRATIVE: Adapted to Scioto Valley.

NAME: Oklahoma Silvermine
NARRATIVE: White dent. Stalks 9-10'. 15 years selection in Virginia.

NAME: Comstock Family Flint
NARRATIVE: Flint. Selected for earliness every year. Matures in about 85 days, usually planted in June and harvested in September. Both kernel colors are planted.
COLLECTION SITE: From the Comstock family, Alstead, New Hampshire. Has been in this family for 50 years.

NAME: Old Wisconsin Red
NARRATIVE: Red and yellow dent. Ears 10 to 20cm long, 10 to 18 rows.

NAME: White Cap Yellow Dent (Landis strain)
NARRATIVE: Cobs to 20cm long, white and red. Seeds yellow dent, white caps. From D. Brubaker.

NAME: Wampum Flint
NARRATIVE: Maturity about 120 days.
COLLECTION SITE: Upper St. Lawrence River Valley, Rooseveltown, New York

NAME: Early Butler (Pennsylvania Farmer Cullo)
NARRATIVE: Yellow dent strain of Early Butler. AES maturity 200. Plants high yielding, fast dry down and susceptible to stalk lodging. Originally from Hoffman Seed Co., Landisville, Pennsylvania
COLLECTION SITE: Obtained from Hoffman Seed Co., Landisville, Pennsylvania.

NAME: Cedaredge Special
NARRATIVE: McDowell was supplied this corn by C. Englehart, a seed dealer in Fruita.  Englehart was supplied the corn by Tony Serve of Loma who had grown it for 15 years.  Serve received it from John Eckert of Eckert in the Cedaredge area who had grown it for at least 20 years.  Eckert may have crossed this variety with Bloody Butcher at one time.

NAME: Wachter's True Gold
NARRATIVE: NA
COLLECTION SITE: 1 mile north and 1 mile west of Yuma, Yuma County.

NAME: Yellow Dent
NARRATIVE: Variety originated from northeast of Wray in 1956.
COLLECTION SITE: 18 miles northeast of Burlington, Kit Carson County.

NAME: Yellow Dent
NARRATIVE: Original source of variety is believed to be Homer Wheeler of Eckley who had grown this corn for many years.
COLLECTION SITE: 14 miles northwest of Wray, Yuma County.

NAME: Iowa Silvermine
NARRATIVE: About 1954, Serve got this corn from Mr. Castor, who in turn got it from Mr. Nowles of Fruita.  However, Serve did not grow the corn until about 1957.
COLLECTION SITE: 4 miles west of Fruita, or 1 1/2 miles southeast of Loma, Mesa County.
